Literally.

00:22:20.860 --> 00:22:23.050 align:middle line:84%
They-- when you
control the power

00:22:23.050 --> 00:22:24.760 align:middle line:84%
grid, which is
something I think needs

00:22:24.760 --> 00:22:26.215 align:middle line:90%
to end and be decentralized.

00:22:26.215 --> 00:22:28.090 align:middle line:84%
And that's one of the
beautiful things that's

00:22:28.090 --> 00:22:32.590 align:middle line:84%
happening with solar, is we're
getting a lot of distributed

00:22:32.590 --> 00:22:33.769 align:middle line:90%
inputs to the grid.

00:22:33.769 --> 00:22:35.560 align:middle line:84%
And I think there's
other technologies that

00:22:35.560 --> 00:22:37.510 align:middle line:84%
have been withheld
from us that could

00:22:37.510 --> 00:22:41.480 align:middle line:84%
complete that transition to a
distributed electronic grid.

00:22:41.480 --> 00:22:43.750 align:middle line:84%
So because they have
a centralized system,

00:22:43.750 --> 00:22:47.110 align:middle line:84%
they can manipulate the movement
of electricity across the lines

00:22:47.110 --> 00:22:50.530 align:middle line:84%
that they have to buy
time on, by capacity.

00:22:50.530 --> 00:22:53.590 align:middle line:84%
And so if you've got
the LA Basin, when

00:22:53.590 --> 00:22:56.680 align:middle line:84%
you get into the interior
it's 102, 103 degrees.

00:22:56.680 --> 00:22:57.760 align:middle line:90%
It's not comfortable.

00:22:57.760 --> 00:23:00.304 align:middle line:84%
We don't build a
building in the desert.

00:23:00.304 --> 00:23:01.220 align:middle line:90%
How brilliant is that?

